    pearls: ["Always perform auscultation BEFORE palpation and percussion during abdominal assessment; palpation can alter bowel sounds and produce inaccurate findings","The focused assessment is NOT a shortcut; it is a deliberate, evidence-based selection of relevant assessment techniques guided by clinical reasoning based on the chief complaint","Use the PQRST mnemonic for comprehensive pain and symptom assessment: Provokes/Palliates, Quality, Region/Radiation, Severity, Timing","Compare all focused assessment findings to the patient's established baseline; a blood pressure of 90/60 may be normal for one patient and indicate shock in another","Document assessment findings using objective, measurable terms rather than subjective descriptions: write 2+ pitting edema bilateral lower extremities rather than legs slightly swollen","The head-to-toe assessment follows a cephalocaudal (head-to-toe) and proximal-to-distal approach to ensure systematic and complete examination without omissions"],
